The estimates of mean WTP were multiplied by the relevant populations to arrive at aggregate WTP estimates.
The study author developed a conservative lower-bound estimate by assuming that those not responding to the survey had a WTP of zero.
The higher estimate assumes that non-respondents would have the same WTP as respondents.
As shown, the aggregate willingness to pay for Washington residents only is estimated to be between $94 and $138 million per year for 10 years (consistent with the wording of the survey question).
The extrapolation to the remainder of the U.S. population yields very large estimates of annual willingness to pay, between $3.4 and $6.1 billion.
