7-20
The estimated total change in benefits can be placed on a marginal basis as demonstrated in Exhibit 7-9.
This curve is derived by dividing the aggregate change in benefits at each flow level by the change in flow (expressed in cubic feet per second).
Therefore, the curve maps the annual aggregate marginal willingness to pay at each flow level, i.e., the sum that all annual visitors would pay for an additional unit of flow.
For example, when flows are at 200 cfs, the marginal willingness to pay for an additional cfs of water is $650.
As is typical, the marginal benefit derived from moderate flow levels is high and decreases as flow levels increase; i.e., the added increment to aesthetic enjoyment is small at very high flow levels.
